<br>
RP is the playing a role within a given axiom.<br>
<br>
The axiom we are given in EQ has different races who have their own goals, and some of those goals pit them against other races and peoples. The Orcs in Crushbone are trying to expand into the Greater Feydark. They are hostile to Elves because they are competing for that area. The People of Qeynos are in conflict with the Gnolls because the Gnolls are hostile towards them - which is because the Gnolls want the land the other people have settled in.<br>
<br>
There are hundreds of examples of such hostilities. Vah Shir v Grimmlings, the Grimmling/Sonic Wolf/Owlbear war in Hollowshade. The Velious affair. I'm not familiar with them all, but I keep tripping over examples as I wander from land to land!<br>
<br>
We take the roles of some of the people for some of the races. We can't be Orcs, Gnolls or Grimmlings, but we can be Elves, Dwarves, Vah Shir etc. and with that, we are starting out playing a race that is involved with hostilities with other races who are highly unlikely to listen to diplomacy (be interesting if you could, though <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :p --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/tongue.gif ALT=":p"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  )<br>
<br>
So we have conflict, and we are playing our characters with that in mind, and so we strive to survive, to better ourselves and... to help our allies against what ever evil (subjective evil, of cause) there is pitted against us.<br>
<br>
Trust?<br>
<br>
Not really - but try consent. When we log in, we consent to obey Sony's rules to play *their* game on *their* servers.<br>
<br>
Conflict RP is okay, so long as those involved are consenting to take part.  If people aren't comfortable with some aspect of a RP situation, then they can ask to be left out - and if they do, then you must stop as far as they are concerned. Not going into specifics, but rules of common sense should apply. To try forcing or inflicting some aspect of roleplaying on another that you like but they don't can lead to bigger problems and claims of harassment. That's something I think is best avoided. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=dender>dender</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 58<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(8/20/03 9:16 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3907.topic&index=27>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Why can't I have conflict Role-play?</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>The game is the setting, if you are playing eq for the mechanics you must be some sort of masochist.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
