<br>
Exactly, Meledi. Too bad some of the people you cited can't agree to this. Its a shame that some people let RP interfere with other peoples enjoyment of the game.<br>
<br>
Caemus, you seem to be exactly the type of person whose RP I am trying to avoid on the server as much as possible. I do not want 'anything goes' RP with strangers, sorry. I don't think there's anything wrong with my attitude. If i get to know you, OOC, maybe I will RP with you. Until then, sorry, no dice (pun intended).<br>
<br>
I RP with a large group on a weekly basis in a tabletop game. I have gamed with some of these people for 15 to 18 years. I also run games at conventions from time-to-time. The kind of RP that I conduct in my home game is not even remotely close to convention RP. 'Anything goes' does not fly in many convention settings. I don't find it fun to have some other person's RP style inflicted on me. Nor do I feel that it is OK for me to do the reverse. I much prefer a stilted, polite RP style with strangers that while to many of you might seem vanilla seems to me to be the best.<br>
<br>
This being said the conflict between the Fellowship and the Necropolis is consensual and probably in the spirit of fun and is, IMO, part of what the server is here for. The Fellowship people and the Necropolis people mostly trust each other to not cross each other's lines. But, here is the clincher: I do not. I have seen OOC hurt inflicted by members of both groups on persons near to them in retribution for perceived IC problems. I really think that most people don't realize the kind of sick seriousness that some people regard their RP as.<br>
<br>
After numerous attempts at RP, I have had only a few positive experiences and innumerable negative experiences. Time and again it boils down to a big issue with 'Anything Goes.' For those of you who enjoy it, have fun.<br>
<br>
But I ask you this, roleplayers, please respect the boundaries of those of us who do not. We still will help you in the game and want to meet you but we are not willing to RP yet with you. We don't care that your Iksar monk considers us a food source, we are going to /em is not an RPer, please stop. We don't care that your Dwarf of Brell doesn't want us to kill the Dain for RP reasons. We don't want to be shunted to a suboridinate because your GL won't speak to elves when there is a conflict between your RP guild and our AntiRP guild over a spawn. We don't want your RP raid leader insulting a member of our raid until she cries (OOC I might add) because she happened to RP with him once. We are allowed to be out of character and we are entitled to OOC dealings as such. If you cannot respect these wishes, do not expect us to respect your RP.<br>
<br>
As far as the 'why are you here if you don't RP' people go, Calvin/Raijen said it best but I shall embellish. We came here for a virgin server. We tried to RP. Some of us tried a LOT. We got sick of the RP but our friends are here so here we remain. Many of you who are saying 'why are you here if you don't RP?' are people who many of us had huge problems with. We stopped RPing because we didn't like your RP.<br>
<br>
Maybe, just maybe, if you want the RP to thrive you should consider compromising instead of insistence that it is 'your way or the highway' to other RPers, new and old. Otherwise you, the RPers, will remain your own worst enemies. <p><!--EZCODE CENTER START--><div style="text-align:center">Nakath Thunderbush<br>
