You are of course entitled to your OOC dealings in a game but I don't see how you can impose your OOC attitude upon RP'ers any more than RP'ers could impose their attitude upon you.  When I roleplay in this or any game I have no control over how others react to me.  I don't message them and say, &quot;I'm going to say this..you should say this in response...respond to me in RP style or I will not deal with you...&quot;<br>
<br>
You may not care about these things but what bearing does that have on how others feel or play?  None whatsoever actually...you only effect your own reactions and gameplay.  If I were in a group with someone that spoke elvish and I didn't want to respond to them for RP reasons then I won't.  That person may not be roleplaying but that doesn't mean I have to change my playstyle if I don't want to any more than they should have to either.  We can either deal with each other or one of us can leave.  Your statement really doesn't make a lot of sense.<br>
<br>
There is no way whatsoever that RP could interfere with another person's enjoyment of this game.  It's a big world and if you don't want to interact with another person then you absolutely don't have to.  There are in game mechanics like /ignore that can keep your chat window from being spammed with evil not-your-brand-RP (whatever that is).  If I want to emote about eating halfling flesh...how in the world would that possibly effect you?  If I were to RP something along those lines and you sent me a /tell saying you weren't an RPer and to please stop I would have some pretty good laughs actually because it would seem totally ridiculous that that would bother you at all.  Are you a halfling?  Has your family been plagued by cannibalistic Dark Elves?  You've established you aren't interested in RPing unless it's very strictly along your own personal lines so how would me RPing for fun along this vein effect you at all?<br>
<br>
If I am in an RP guild and my guildmaster refuses to speak to you because of your race how does that effect you at all?  If they don't want to break character to resolve your OOC dispute that's their decision.  If you feel slighted because you were relegated to a second class citizen in an RP environment for RP reasons so what?  Who is to say that someone should have to compromise their playstyle over yours?<br>
<br>
A member of your group wants to abstain from killing something for roleplay reasons then so what?  He gives his RP reasons, I assume you give your OOC reasons, you decide to kill it or not and then you will each react however...<br>
<br>
Point is, you're taking your OOC attitude a little overboard.  If someone is effecting your happiness with some in game/in character reactions and that imposes on your powergamer play style then the problem really lies there with you, not with some random RPer.<br>
